{{Infobox medical person |name = Emerson Colon Angell |image = |caption = |birth_date = {{birth date|1822|8|3}} |birth_place = |death_date = |death_place = |profession = [[Dentist]] |specialism = |research_field = |known_for = Father of Rapid maxillary expansion in Orthodontic treatment |years_active = |education = |work_institutions = |prizes = |relations = }}
'''Emerson Colon Angell''' (1822-1903) was an American Dentist who is known as the father of the rapid maxillary expansion.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Timms|first=D. J.|date=1997-05-01|title=Emerson C. Angell (1822-1903). Founding father of rapid maxillary expansion|journal=Dental Historian: Lindsay Club Newsletter|issue=32|pages=3–12|issn=0958-6687|pmid=9879204}}</ref> He published a paper in [[Journal of the American Dental Association|Dental Cosmos]] in 1860 in which he described this technique.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Timms|first=D. J.|date=1999-06-01|title=The dawn of rapid maxillary expansion|journal=The Angle Orthodontist|volume=69|issue=3|pages=247–250|doi=10.1043/0003-3219(1999)069<0247:TDORME>2.3.CO;2|issn=0003-3219|pmid=10371430}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uGZvXAqCkMgC|title=Textbook of Orthodontics|last=Singh|first=Gurkeerat|date=2008-12-01|publisher=Jaypee Brothers Publishers|isbn=9788184480801|language=en}}</ref>
==Life== He was born and grew up in [[Scituate, Rhode Island]]. He was the 7th generation of his family from Rhode Island. He was descendant of [[Thomas Angell]]. Emerson learned agriculture and mechanics from his father. He began studying dentistry in 1846 under mentorship of people in the community due to the lack of any formal education available at that time. He eventually practiced in Rhode Island, New York City and San Francisco.
==Dentistry== Emerson first published a paper on expansion of palate in [[San Francisco Medical Press]] (SFMP) in January 1960.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hirsch|first=G. P.|date=1977-06-01|title=Palatal expansion - adjunct to dentofacial orthopedics|journal=International Journal of Orthodontics|volume=15|issue=2|pages=23–29, 46|issn=0020-7500|pmid=328420}}</ref> This initial paper described the expansion of palate with deciduous teeth which was later followed by another paper on the permanent teeth dentition in SFMP. His first paper was a case report which focused on a 14-year-old patient with a posterior [[Crossbite]]. Emerson fitted this patient with an appliance in his maxillary arch and gave patients instructions to turn screw everyday. Emerson claimed that expansion was achieved in 2 weeks by separation of maxilla along the [[Midpalatal suture]] . Dr. Angell faced much criticism from people in the field of dentistry at that point.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Philippe|first=Julien|date=2007-04-01|title=The origin of treatment expansion|journal=American Journal of Orthodontics and Dentofacial Orthopedics|volume=131|issue=4|pages=446; author reply 446|doi=10.1016/j.ajodo.2007.02.044|issn=1097-6752|pmid=17418705}}</ref>
